A Protestant Lutheran chapel was built in the 13th century. An adjoining cloister was added in the 15th century when the church was rebuilt. After many modifications and reconstructions, the current church dates from the 18th century and was attached to the Lutheran cult at the beginning of the 19th century. The cloister, also modified and restored, is the only cloister preserved from the Middle Ages in Paris. These 2 places are only partially open: day and time. The Lutheran church is open Thursday and Sunday. The cloister is only open for temporary exhibitions.

Located in the heart of the marsh, this Lutheran and Protestant church of Billettes has a history closely linked to that of Paris. Don't hesitate to visit it and ask the pastor who is passionate about the history of Paris to tell you about it! This superb, very old church hosts many concerts, especially music but also songs and gospels. You should not leave without having visited the billet cloister next to the Church. This cloister hosts exhibitions but also works by artists from all over the world. It's completely free!
